description.plain: With their thoroughly modern disco sound — a blend of house, funk, electro and techno — this French duo was one of the biggest electronic music acts of the late 1990s and 2000s. Guy Manuel de Homem-Christo and Thomas Bangalter wore shiny droid costumes at every live show (and only allowed themselves to be photographed in said costumes) but their music was only sometimes robotic: Daft Punk were as influenced by rock bands like AC/DC as they were by classic disco acts (Chic’s Nile Rodgers even collaborated with them later).

description.plain:
Featuring vocals from renowned singer-songwriter Paul Williams, this song marks the midpoint of Random Access Memories and seems to possibly continue where “Within” left off.

Opening with a bizarre segment consisting of warped sines and synths, this track takes cues from the work of the late electronic composer Karlheinz Stockhausen before taking listeners on a genre-bending ride that spans electronic, ragtime, and orchestral music.

Paul’s vocals seep in and out of the song, longing for not only the physical, but emotional “touch” of other people after an extended period of time in isolation. The speaker may have had plenty of time to think and reflect while in their lonesome, but after looking inside themselves, they realize that they are missing something, and need “something more” to be fulfilled and feel truly human.

description.plain:
One of Daft Punk’s most popular and famous singles, “Harder Better Faster Stronger” draws you in with it’s catchy beat, irresistible electronic vocals, and fun lyrical wordplay. Put together like an assembly line, this song begins as just disconnected lines and words, but in the end, these words come together to form coherent phrases and sentences.

The single cover is the only one that explicitly draws from Interstella 5555: The 5tory of the 5ecret 5tar 5ystem  - showing how the anime uses the song to score the blue alien band going through a machine that makes them look human.

The song’s limited lyrics were also exploited in the viral video “Daft Hands” (which in turn inspired a full-bodied performance, “Daft Bodies”).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2cYWfq--Nw

The song was sampled in Kanye West’s “Stronger”.

description.plain:
“Beyond” deals with a multitude of various themes which have been recurrent throughout the album. The most straightforward message of the song is to allow and push oneself to simply go “beyond” in life. Go beyond your dreams, go beyond love, lose control and reach for that higher state of being.

This elevated emotional state is subtly compared to that of God, as the human consciousness is what spurns these ideas of love and dreams, and can create an internal world all on it’s own, while also influencing the real world with it’s affects on life and understanding. The world we live in and how understand it is all based on perception, so one’s mind is truly the “end and the beginning” of everything we know and feel.

All those knowing listeners who bought Homework and signed on for the pair’s rascally, nudge-wink grooves now have to figure out what part of “One More Time” is for them. Is there a subversive part of “One More Time?” If so, where does it begin?

description.plain:
Leaked in 2014, “Computerized” is the perfect storm of rap, rock, and electronica, a collaboration between the biggest rapper in the world, Jay Z, and the biggest dance artist in the world, Daft Punk.

Hov had previously rapped with a twinge of disdain for ubiquitous technology, but here, he makes that theme explicit, arguing that we abbreviate our relationships and our lives through the constant use of phones and devices. Of course, this gels perfectly with Daft Punk’s major theme of blurring the lines between technology and humanity, expressed so well in songs like “Robot Rock” and “Technologic” (and, of course, in their costumes).



Rumours circling the track’s early leak placed Kanye West at the co-producer helm; however, despite his previous work with the Parisian duo on 2013’s Rap Genius album of the year Yeezus and 2007’s “Stronger,” Pitchfork confirmed that his involvement was exactly that, a rumour.

In 2016 it was revealed the track was recorded for Daft Punk’s TRON: Legacy soundtrack, after Walt Disney Records “tortured” the duo for a single. It was eventually deemed “too rooted in real life” for it to be appropriate, and so was never released.

description.plain:
Interstella 5555: The 5tory of the 5ecret 5tar 5ystem is the animated imagining of the concept album Discovery which was released in March 2001.

After the album was produced, Daft Punk presented the idea of it being made into an animated film to Leiji Matsumoto, a Japanese animator most famous for directing the space-opera Space Battleship Yamato in 1974, and the two 1977 TV series which Daft Punk were fans of: Space Pirate Captain Harlock and Galaxy Express 999.

The film cost $4million to produce, eventually being released in May, 2003.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h5-FJsYj1ck

It is essentially the whole Discovery album, with no additional dialogue, scoring a The Man Who Fell to Earth-esque story about aliens disguised as humans who become famous.

description.plain:
Daft Punk are famous for their incredibly advanced robot-style helmets. The band’s aesthetic has focused around them since Discovery and the band have not made a public appearance without them since Human After All.

Daft Punk use this aesthetic to tranform their music into true performance, often sacrificing visibility and practicality for effects. Any time the helmets featured LED displays, the band members had pin-sized eyeholes to view out of rather than the full visor.



Thomas has explained the reasoning behind the masks, stating:


We don’t believe in the [celebrity ]star[dom]system. We want the focus to be on the music. If we have to create an image, it must be an artificial image. That combination hides our physicality and also shows our view of the star system. It is not a compromise.

We’re trying to separate the private side and the public side. It’s just that we’re a little bit embarrassed by the whole thing. We don’t want to play this star system thing. We don’t want to get recognised in the streets. Yes. Everyone has accepted us using masks in photos so far, which makes us happy. Maybe sometimes people are a little bit disappointed but that’s the only way we want to do it. We think the music is the most personal thing we can give. The rest is just about people taking themselves seriously, which is all very boring sometimes.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QPrmJr0Jj3k

If you’re wondering what part of the song was sampled it’s the synth in the beginning.

description.plain: Originally recorded nearly two decades earlier, Daft Punk made this track along with their very first singles under Soma Records. Recorded in 1994, around the time of “Da Funk”, this remained unreleased until Soma celebrated their 20 Year Anniversary with the release of a collection of classics and unreleased gems. This contained Daft Punk’s “Drive.” There is an additional song that was on the reverse side of the “Drive” DAT-tape. “Drive” was chosen to be released by the band between the two tracks. To the dismay of fans, it is unknown whether the additional track will ever be released.

description.plain: Debated for its legitimacy many times by fans, this remix surfaced as early as 2008, but had never been officially released until Daft Punk silently gave the Japan-only remix album of their third album, Human After All: Remixes, a re-release in Japan in 2014. Following this, the duo released the album on streaming services with this additional remix. This remix, done by French electronic duo Le Knight Club (made up of members Éric Chedeville and Daft Punk’s own Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo) was included exclusively on the digital release, confirming its validity.
